name: Nancy Pelosi
content:
Juneteenth is a beautiful and proud celebration of freedom for Black Americans commemorated for 156 years by millions around our nation. It marks the day, two years after President Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, when Major General Gordon Granger and Union soldiers delivered the news of liberation in Galveston, Texas. Over the past century and half, Juneteenth has evolved into a day of not only celebration, but of reflection. This day reminds us of a history much stained by brutality and injustice and reminds us of our responsibility to build a future of progress for all, honoring the ideal of equality that is America's heritage and America's hope.

Thank you to the Congressional Black Caucus, Texas Delegation and all Members who have worked for this official recognition over many years. With this step, Congress is ensuring that one of the most momentous events in our history, which has been celebrated by millions, particularly Black Americans, for 150 years now is officially recognized, enshrined in our history books and takes its place of honor in our nation. The Democratic House remains committed to real, effective action to advance justice, fairness and opportunity for all. I am honored to be here with the Black Caucus, as it is the conscience of the House of Representatives.

name: Nancy Pelosi
content:
Today’s unanimous ruling by the Supreme Court made clear: discrimination has no place in our foster and adoption systems, or anywhere in our democracy. While the decision was not a sweeping victory, Americans are proud that the Court affirmed that LGBTQ couples have a right to welcome children in our foster care system into their families.

As a nation, our most important responsibility is to provide for the health, education and well-being of our children – and no child should be denied a loving and caring home because of the sexuality or gender identity of their foster parents. House Democrats are proud to have joined this fight, filing an amicus brief in this case asserting our opposition to the deeply offensive effort to sacrifice the well-being of the thousands of children in the foster care system to push a bigoted anti-LGBTQ agenda.

LGBTQ couples have faced a long history of discrimination in public life, especially while trying to build a family. Under the leadership of Democrats in Congress and the Biden-Harris Administration, we will not relent until the House-passed Equality Act becomes the law of the land. Today, let us recommit to the fight for full equality and build a more just future for all Americans.

name: Tim Kaine
content:
Juneteenth commemorates an important element of the American story, and I’m happy that it will finally become a federal holiday. This is a story about the African-American community overcoming adversity, and it’s an important reminder about the work still ahead. This Juneteenth and onward, let’s remember that we’re stronger as a nation when we live up to our pledge of liberty and justice for all.

name: Christopher Murphy
content:
Too many students, especially kids of color and those with disabilities, are being arrested at school, often for minor school discipline issues that quickly escalate and unnecessarily involve police. On top of that, 10 million students attend schools with police but no social workers.

It’s time we provide children with the school-based support system they need to feel safe and succeed.

That's why today, I'm re-introducing legislation to establish a $5 billion grant program to hire more counselors, social workers, nurses, school psychologists and other support staff in schools – rather than put more police in schools.

But let's be clear: my bill doesn't prohibit schools from hiring police officers. It just says that federal dollars should be directed toward hiring counselors instead of police.

Let's reform our school discipline system. Let's support our students. Let's pass the Counseling Not Criminalization in Schools Act.

name: Thomas Massie
content:
It's not scientific to force our troops to take the COVID-19 vaccine. Last night, I joined Kennedy to discuss legislation I have introduced (HR 3860) to prohibit any requirement for members of the Armed Forces to receive a vaccination.

Males aged 18 to 24 represent the category least susceptible to COVID and most likely to have an adverse reaction called "myocarditis," a swelling of the heart. Why submit our troops to this risk, especially if they already have natural immunity due to recovery from a previous COVID infection?

I introduced this bill because I have constituents in the military who are telling me they will face a general discharge if they refuse the vaccine. Why would we want to force people out of the military just because they believe in science?

Currently, HR 3860 has 13 cosponsors. They are: U.S. Representative Chip Roy Press Office, Rep. Lance Gooden, Congresswoman Marjorie Taylor Greene, Congresswoman Lauren Boebert, Rep. Scott Perry, Congressman Greg Steube, Congressman Andy Biggs, Congressman Andrew Clyde, Congressman Tim Burchett, Congressman Jeff Duncan, Rep. Paul Gosar, Congressman Alex Mooney, and Louie Gohmert.

Over the last twelve years, the Affordable Care Act has helped more than a hundred million Americans access lifesaving medical care – and over the past year-plus, a once-in-a-generation pandemic drove home the importance of quality, accessible, affordable healthcare. After Americans witnessed the physical, emotional and economic costs of COVID-19, the health coverage and protections guaranteed by the ACA are more important than ever. name: Tina Smith
content:
Today Juneteenth becomes a federal holiday, and I stood behind Vice President Harris and President Biden to watch our bill be signed into law.

This has been a hard year, filled with trauma and worry, loss and hardship. So it feels good to celebrate this important and unifying moment. We didn’t know until minutes before our bill passed the Senate that it would even get done, but we did it—all of a sudden after decades of organizing and advocating by so many.

Here are a few impressions: The White House is a small big place. It’s a beautiful building filled with grand rooms, cramped offices, private places and some of the most public and famous views in the world. It was built by enslaved people, and today Congress still denies the city’s residents—many of them Black—the right to be represented in Congress. Our remarkable Vice President, Kamala Harris, the first woman and first Black Vice President, spoke today with deep conviction about the meaning of Juneteenth, and the work we have ahead. Our President celebrated 95-year-old Ms. Opal Lee, who has organized and advocated for Juneteenth for decades, dropping down on one knee to greet her. I’ve gotten to know Ms. Lee over the last few years, and have followed her leadership. Her persistence and joy is absolutely infectious. There is a celebratory picture with me and Ms. Opal Lee and Usher, himself a passionate advocate for Juneteenth. Usher and I were starstruck. Whoever took that picture, thank you!

All of us at the White House today celebrated this moment, and also understood that today is only one more paving stone on the long path of toward justice and freedom we need to build together. This newest federal holiday can help propel us forward, and give us energy for the work ahead on voting rights, economic and environmental justice, policing and criminal justice reform, so we can fulfill the promise of this country.

It was remarkable to be with leaders of the Congressional Black Caucus who have worked for decades to get this done. Most especially I was so blessed to sit next to Ms. Opal Lee, who has organized and advocated on behalf of Juneteenth harder than anyone I know. And I was so incredibly honored to join her today.

name: Tammy Duckworth
content:
Despite more than a decade of relentless attacks from Republicans aimed at ripping healthcare away from millions of Americans, today’s resounding Supreme Court decision reaffirms—for the third time by the nation’s highest court—that the Affordable Care Act is the law of the land.

This is a great day for the 31 million Americans who rely on the Obama-Biden Administration’s landmark health coverage law, for 135 million people who—like me—have pre-existing conditions and for the millions of uninsured people who have access to high-quality, affordable coverage because of the Affordable Care Act.

I am hopeful that after a decade of harmful efforts to rip care away from millions and three losses in the Supreme Court, Republicans might finally be willing to work with Democrats to strengthen healthcare in this country and make sure even more hardworking people across the country can get covered. And I hope that anyone who wants health coverage during this pandemic takes advantage of the Special Enrollment Period that President Biden created to find an expanded, low-cost plan that’s right for them before the August 15th deadline.

name: Ralph Norman
content:
It was a unanimous 9-0 decision by the Supreme Court earlier today. And a huge win for religious liberties. Long story short:

1. Catholic Social Services (CSS) is one of numerous agencies that provides foster placement services in the Philadelphia area.

2. As a Catholic organization, CSS has faith-based objections to placing foster children with same-sex couples.

3. As a result, the City of Philadelphia refused to enter into contracts with CSS for foster services based on their religious objections.

4. Earlier today, the Supreme Court had the final say, ruling unanimously that Philly was wrong, and had been violating the First Amendment rights of Catholic Social Services.

Same sex couples still obviously have a variety of other foster agency options, so it's not like they're being denied anything when CSS has faith-based objections. In a well-worded excerpt from one of the majority opinions, Chief Justice John Roberts said that Catholic Social Services "seeks only an accommodation that will allow it to continue serving the children of Philadelphia in a manner consistent with its religious beliefs; it does not seek to impose those beliefs on anyone else." That's about as clear as it gets.

There are other cases in the judicial pipeline similar in nature, including one here in South Carolina for Miracle Hill Ministries, another faith-based agency. Hopefully today's decision is a good indicator for those religious organizations.

https://www.foxnews.com/politics/supreme-court-decision-religious-freedom-backlash-left

name: Lisa Murkowski
content:
Today the President signed a bill into law establishing Juneteenth, the date commemorating the end of slavery in the United States, as a federal holiday. Juneteenth marks the date that the last enslaved African Americans were granted their freedom on June 19, 1865. On that day African Americans in Galveston, Texas learned that they had been freed nearly two and a half years earlier when President Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation. While Juneteenth has long been celebrated in our communities, this kind of a designation and recognition is the right step and long overdue—a reminder to reflect on the fundamental shift in the direction of our country.

NMAAHC.SI.EDU
The Historical Legacy of Juneteenth

name: James M. Inhofe
content:
This week, I had the honor of administering the Oath of Office to one of our summer interns, officially commissioning him into the United States Air Force.

This Oath of Office is one that has been administered since April 1790; and since then, it has served as a reminder of one’s obligation to their service, their country and their commitment to defend the Constitution of the United States. As someone who also takes an oath to defend the Constitution, I am encouraged to know that 2d Lt. Harvey will dedicate his military career to that pursuit.

I am proud to have 2d Lt. Harvey as an intern this summer, and I look forward to seeing him succeed in the years ahead.

name: Richard Blumenthal
content:
After years of relentless attacks aimed at restricting & denying millions of Americans health care access, today's ruling reaffirms what we’ve always known—the ACA is constitutional. Americans can begin to breathe a sigh of relief, these health care protections are here to stay.

This decisive decision will allow millions of Americans to sleep a little easier tonight. After all the absurd legal contortions in this challenge, today’s decision should be no surprise, but it is a profound relief.

For years, ACA’s opponents have seemingly stopped at nothing in their quest to decimate this law, using increasingly desperate strategies. After this resounding legal defeat, Republicans should finally abandon their cruel & reckless attempt to undermine health care protections.

name: Angus S. King, Jr.
content:
Cyberattacks are becoming a weapon of choice for nation-states and criminals alike in the 21st century – and as an open, widely-connected society, the United States has asymmetrical vulnerabilities that it must work to address. In recent weeks, America has been hit by a number of disruptive cyberattacks, and the only thing more chilling than the steady stream of attacks is the knowledge that in the wrong hands, the effects could be far more devastating.

We are receiving wake-up call after wake-up call that America needs to bolster its cyberdefenses. Today, the Senate took a historic step toward confronting this challenge by confirming Chris Inglis as the country’s first-ever National Cyber Director. Chris is an intelligent and talented leader, who possesses both the experience and the disposition to lead a government-wide effort to strengthen our cybersecurity. I thank President Biden for selecting him – after working beside him for years in the Cyberspace Solarium Commission, I believe he is the best person for the job, and I look forward to our continued partnership on this urgent issue.

In the days ahead, I will continue working with my Congressional colleagues to ensure Chris has the resources he needs to succeed in this vital task – including providing adequate funding to build out the Office of the National Cyber Director and giving him a talented partner in this fight by confirming Jen Easterly to serve as Director of the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency.

POLITICO.COM

name: Robert C. "Bobby" Scott
content:
Today, the Supreme Court threw out yet another baseless lawsuit against the Affordable Care Act (ACA). The Court’s decision will protect millions of Americans’ access to affordable health care, secure coverage for people with pre-existing conditions, and maintain critical protections that patients rely on every day.

As we continue to confront the worst public health emergency in recent history, our first priority must be to protect Americans’ health and wellbeing. This frivolous legal challenge – brought by a group of Republican Attorneys General and supported by the Trump administration – is the latest example of Republicans’ relentless effort to sabotage and dismantle our nation’s health care system.

My colleagues and I will not only continue to protect these lifesaving protections from partisan attacks, but we will also work to expand access and reduce costs. Our goal is to ensure that every American has access to high-quality, affordable health care.

name: Mike Bost
content:
Experts say that as much as $400 billion, HALF of all COVID-19 unemployment benefits, may have been stolen over the past year, much of it by foreign criminals. This is completely unacceptable and is exactly why I called for more oversight over the distribution of these funds a year ago.

https://www.axios.com/pandemic-unemployment-fraud-benefits-stolen-a937ad9d-0973-4aad-814f-4ca47b72f67f.html

Rep. Mike Bost
July 27, 2020 at 4:01 PM ·

In recent weeks I was mailed an $8,800 unemployment debit card from the State of Illinois and a $6,500 unemployment debit card from the State of California. I have never filed for unemployment benefits and the only time I have spent in California was in the Marine Corps 40 years ago. I have personally contacted state and federal authorities to get to the bottom of this.

No doubt, the coronavirus shutdown has had a crushing impact on our economy and working families. We need to get help to the people who need it. But we have got to have some common sense oversight in how these funds are distributed.

name: Ed Perlmutter
content:
Today’s ruling by the Supreme Court leaves the Affordable Care Act as the law of the land and saves health care coverage for hundreds of thousands of Coloradans and millions of Americans.

Affordable health care is a civil right. Every person deserves high-quality, affordable medical coverage regardless of their age, pre-existing conditions, or income level. The Affordable Care Act has provided certainty for millions of people, and today’s decision will continue to provide access to dependable and affordable health care for folks across Colorado and the U.S.

Rather than continue their attacks on the ACA, I urge Republicans to work across the aisle to continue to improve the ACA to ensure it can continue to provide affordable, accessible health care coverage for all Americans.

name: Doris O. Matsui

Today, the Supreme Court struck down the Republicans’ latest attempt to dismantle the #AffordableCareAct and take away health care from millions of Americans. Despite the relentless efforts of Republicans, today’s ruling is a crucial victory in our continued fight to #ProtectOurCare, protect Americans with pre-existing conditions, improve health equity, and expand access to care.

The #ACA has been a lifeline to millions of Americans — expanding Medicaid eligibility, establishing the individual marketplace, providing subsidies and tax credits to make coverage more affordable, and ensuring health plans cover essential benefits for every American. It has made sure that historically underserved Americans are no longer priced out or shut out of the coverage they need.

The Affordable Care Act is here to stay, and now we must continue to deliver accessible and affordable #healthcare for the American people.

name: Warren Davidson
content:
Yesterday, the House voted to make Juneteenth a Federal Holiday. I voted “yes” on this bill.

Here’s an excerpt of my speech urging its passage:

“The long struggle in defense of freedom is part of America’s history. At our Founding, in the Declaration of Independence, our founders eloquently stated that all people are endowed by their creator with certain unalienable rights, that among them are life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness. Winning the Revolution offered the potential for leaders like John Adams to rightly persuade their colleagues to end slavery, but they failed.

Their failure set the stage for the Civil War and the failure to complete reconstruction meant 100 years of Jim Crow and “separate but equal” . . . America’s failure to rightly recognize our painful and often unjust history have meant ongoing division and open wounds that continue to fester. So today, let us not fail to persuade our colleagues. Let us recognize this holiday.

It should, however, be known as Freedom Day or simply Juneteenth, not National Independence Day, which recognizes the Declaration, not freedom, but the Declaration of Independence . . . but let’s not allow the perfect to become the enemy of the good.”

name: John Boozman
content:
Democrats continue to push for nationalizing our elections through their power-grabbing S.1 legislation. This bill usurps states' constitutional right to decide how to conduct elections, and it only gets worse from there. It will unleash chaos on our electoral system.

This overreaching federal takeover seizes state's redistricting jurisdiction, publicly finances political campaigns, creates a partisan advantage within the FEC, fuels efforts to cancel and intimidate political speech, and subverts the strength of our system – decentralization.

I joined Senator Cotton, Congresman Hill and Arkansas Secretary of State John Thurston earlier this year to discuss all the flaws of this legislation, and those problems still exist today. I oppose this measure and urge my Democratic colleagues to abandon their attempts to transform our elections for their own advantage.

name: Sam Graves
content:
On this day in history, Secretary of War Henry Stimson called then-Senator Harry S. Truman, warning the Senator to drop his inquiry into a defense plant in Pasco, Washington.

Truman, as Chair of the Special Committee to Investigate the National Defense Program, was conducting an investigation into US war production to eliminate waste, inefficiency, and war profiteering.

After receiving Stimson’s warning and assurance that the plant was “part of a very important secret development,” Truman, veteran of WWI, dropped his plans to investigate the plant. Unknown to Truman at the time, that plant was connected to the Manhattan Project, the program that developed the atomic bomb.

It would be nearly another 2 years before Truman learned about the project, which he was not briefed on until after he was sworn in as President following the death of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt.

Later, he would order the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, Japan, widely credited with helping push the island nation to agree to the terms of an unconditional surrender without necessitating a deadly invasion of the Japanese homeland, which would have cost countless more American and Japanese lives.

That surrender was signed on the deck of the battleship, USS Missouri, on September 2, 1945.

name: Richard Hudson
content:
Today, the House voted to repeal the Authorization for Use of Military Force (AUMF) in Iraq. I believe repealing this AUMF without a replacement is dangerous and risks the lives of our service members at Fort Bragg and stationed around the globe.

No one wants endless wars in the Middle East, and I agree that the current AUMF is outdated and ought to be replaced with a new AUMF that reflects the current threat environment. However, repealing the current AUMF without a replacement exposes our men and women in uniform without a clear legal framework for their current and ongoing missions and limits the President's ability to act swiftly and decisively in response to imminent threats to our national security interests.

name: Bob Gibbs
content:
The VA requires all veterans seeking emergency treatment at non-VA facilities to notify them within 72-hours of admission to the non-VA facility. If they don’t, even if the veteran is suffering from a condition preventing him/her from physically contacting them, the VA may deny payment, regardless of whether the medical issue is service connected.

Today, I introduced the Addressing Care Timelines (ACT) for Veterans Act, which would give veterans an additional 24-hours, four days total, to notify the VA when receiving care at a non-VA facility. When getting immediate medical care outside of the VA system is a veterans’ only option, they should not be worried about bureaucracy and paperwork when they should be focusing on their health.

name: Bill Johnson
content:
The Youngstown/Warren Regional Chamber held their 4th annual “fly-in” today. It was a hybrid virtual event this year, and I spoke and took questions from my office in Washington due to the House being in session. We touched on a number of local issues, including the lack of broadband access. I believe the results of last year’s FCC Rural Digital Opportunity Fund (RDOF) auction is a tremendous opportunity for rural America and, if done correctly, has great potential to help close the urban-rural digital divide. I have worked closely with stakeholders and providers in Eastern and Southeastern Ohio during this process. Broadband access providers who bid in the auction in Mahoning Co. were awarded over $1.2M and bidders in Columbiana County were awarded almost $3M.

We also talked about the important missions the men and women at the Youngstown Air Reserve Station carryout, developments in Lordstown, and the negative impacts of escalating costs on raw materials, fuel and shipping are having on business owners.

American energy independence is crucial to protecting our national security and economy. name: Paul Tonko
content:
We cannot unravel infrastructure from climate. As we consider bold new investments in America’s infrastructure, our choices will shape our climate future, for better or worse.

Failing to address climate pollution and clean energy in our infrastructure work will force future generations of Americans to cover a blank check. And we are already passing on grave and growing costs for our past failures to act.

But let me put this another way: seizing opportunities to tackle climate change in our infrastructure work will help us build legislation that makes America a cleaner, safer, more competitive nation. It will save countless lives and create millions of good, American jobs.

If we make climate a priority, our workers will miss fewer days on the job and our kids will miss fewer days at school.

Our local budgets will suffer less strain, our infrastructure dollars will go farther. The things we build will last longer.

Climate change is a growing threat that demands urgent bold action. And doing nothing about it is doing something— it is condemning the United States to become a weaker, sicker, and poorer nation.

This is our path to choose. Do we allow America to further decline or choose a more sustainable, prosperous, and just future?

To me, a great many of us in Congress, and the vast majority of Americans, the choice is clear. Let’s ensure our infrastructure work can move forward by doing our jobs on climate.

name: Garret Graves
content:
We have an update on the efforts to repeal the Windfall Elimination Penalty (WEP) and the Government Pension Offset (GPO) – two problems that I’m deeply involved in working to solve.

Want to stay in the loop on future WEP/GPO updates?

Visit garretgraves.house.gov/wepgpo and sign up.

Please share this post with friends and family in the community experiencing similar issues.

What's the latest?

Right now, the Social Security Fairness Act currently has 167 bipartisan cosponsors. I will continue working with members of both political parties so that we can reach 290 cosponsors. We're not stopping until leadership of the U.S. House brings the bill to the floor for a vote.

I have co-authored this legislation to fix this penalty, which punishes tens of thousands of Louisiana public servants. We continue pushing for the House to vote on this legislation and if it passes, Louisiana's dedicated public servants and their spouses or survivors will receive the full retirement benefits they deserve, including those who have already retired. It remains among my greatest priorities in Congress.

Public servants in Louisiana (teachers, firefighters, etc.) are some of the most impacted victims of the infamous WEP and GPO – a flawed federal law that can result in massive cuts in their Social Security retirement.

I am proud to lead a bipartisan coalition of members, advocates, and retirees that are fighting in Congress to fix this broken policy because it punishes our public servants for unfounded reasons.

MYEMAIL.CONSTANTCONTACT.COM

name: Warren Davidson
content:
Americans widely recognize that our prolonged presence in Iraq has not made America more secure. As we see a welcome reduction in the number of troops in the Middle East, Congress should rescind the 2002 authorization, which has allowed multiple administrations to maintain a U.S. military presence that no longer bears any resemblance to the language of the authorization.

The mission has changed, and so should the authorization. The current 2002 AUMF serves as a shackle to prevent those updates to align authorizations with missions and actions. That should alarm everyone – and motivate Congress to finally do its duty.

As Donald Trump wisely said, ‘Great nations don’t fight endless wars.’ I’m hopeful that the Senate will act quickly and send this important legislation to the President’s desk.”

WSJ.COM

name: Don Young
content:
NEW: I’m very proud to have once again been awarded the Jefferson-Hamilton Award for Bipartisanship from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce! This award recognizes Members of Congress who demonstrate bipartisan leadership and a commitment to constructive governing.

Bipartisanship is a key component of constructive governing, and I have always valued my relationships with my friends across the aisle. Alaska is unlike any other state, and its people deserve a Congressman who knows how to secure important wins for our unique needs.

Just last month, when countless families in Alaska with livelihoods at risk were facing the loss of another summer cruise season, I worked with Senators Murkowski and Sullivan, House and Senate leadership on both sides of the aisle, and with President Biden to pass the Alaska Tourism Restoration Act. Without bipartisan relationships, this bill wouldn’t have been enacted, and Alaskans would have suffered another devastating loss of income and stability.

Having served in both the majority and minority, I know what it takes to get things done. Read more: https://bit.ly/35yieB4

name: Sean Patrick Maloney
content: This is a disappointing ruling from SCOTUS in Fulton v. Philadelphia. When you allow discrimination against LGBTQ couples and call it religious liberty, you deprive kids like mine of families who will love them. name: Ken Calvert
content: I spoke on the House floor earlier today in opposition to legislation that would repeal Authorization for the Use of Military Force (AUMF) in Iraq. The activities and posture of our military forces in Iraq have varied greatly since the original AUMF was approved by Congress in 2002. The AUMF allowed us to respond and assist the people of Iraq when decisions made by the Obama-Biden Administration led to the formation of ISIS and enabled the terror group to establish a Caliphate in northwestern Iraq in 2014. It also provided the authority for last year’s strike on Iran’s terror mastermind, Qasem Soleimani whose IEDs killed more than 600 American soldiers and wounded thousands more. AUMF also provides authority to strike Iranian-backed Shi’a militia groups who have and are currently attacking Americans in Iraq. While I believe it would be appropriate to consider narrowing the scope of the AUMF, repealing it without any kind of replacement would put American interests in danger as well as embolden Iran and the terror groups it supports.

name: John Garamendi
content: Earlier today, I spoke on the House Floor in support of repealing the 2002 Authorization for the Use of Military Force (AUMF) against Iraq. The US Congress has the sole constitutional power to declare war and, therefore, a Constitutional duty to consider, debate, and -- if necessary -- authorize the use of military force. Since 2009, I have voted consistently to revoke this open-ended authorization and to re-assert Congress' role and ensure that it upholds its Constitutional duty. We have a responsibility to the members of our armed forces who risk their lives to defend us, and to the American public, whose taxpayer dollars fund these seemingly endless conflicts.

name: J. Hill
content:
Over two years ago, I learned of a former Arkansas resident, Majd Kamalmaz, who had been arrested in Syria in 2017 while attending a family member’s funeral. I felt it was my duty to act on behalf of the Kamalmaz family to do what I could to bring Majd home.

According to the James Foley Legacy Foundation, there are more than 50 publicly known Americans wrongfully detained or held hostage abroad.

That is why I launched the American Hostage Task Force - to bring those Americans home. I hosted a bipartisan press conference today with Rep. Deutch announcing the launch of the Congressional Task Force on American Hostages and Americans Wrongfully Detained Abroad. I look forward to working with him and a bipartisan group of like-minded members to help families bring their loved ones home and to educate other members of Congress on how best to advocate for their constituents in similar situations.

I will continue to do everything I can to help bring Americans home and I am inspired by the courage of families with loved ones held abroad, like the Kamalmaz family.

name: Lisa Murkowski
content: Today I spoke on the U.S. Senate floor, urging my colleagues to take up and pass the #VOCAFix Act, legislation I helped introduce in March that will strengthen the Victims of Crime Act (VOCA) by re-directing new funds into the Crime Victims Fund (CVF). There are about 30 organizations in Alaska who have been notified that they may see a 35 percent cut to their funding, effective July 1. This cut is set to affect their funds for not only this year, but the next year going forward. This legislation does not change how federal tax money is spent. It provides a technical fix by directing additional non-taxpayers dollars from criminal monetary penalties into the fund. The longer Congress delays this fix, the larger the cuts that victims services will see. Our providers are calling out to us for help. We simply cannot fail them.

name: Anthony Brown
content:
The 2002 AUMF sent me and hundreds of thousands of servicemen and women to Iraq since the invasion in 2003. Over the course of Operation Iraqi Freedom, our nation has lost more than 4,400 brave soldiers, sailors, airmen and Marines. The justification for this war was fundamentally flawed, yet, I have no doubt that the mission we were given has been completed.

For years, I’ve advocated for the repeal of the 2002 AUMF. It’s time for us, for Congress and the American people, to formally recognize the end of America’s 2002 mission in Iraq.

This is an important first step, as Congress once again reasserts its responsibility in the use of our military forces, through frameworks that address current threats to our nation and authorize the use of military force only as a last resort.

name: Robin L. Kelly
content:
Six years ago today, a white supremacist bought a gun after an incomplete background check and massacred 9 worshippers at Mother Emanuel AME Church in Charleston, South Carolina.

Since then nothing has changed. This March, the House passed the Enhanced Background Checks Act of 2021, H.R. 1446—also called the “Charleston Loophole” bill—to ensure complete and accurate background checks. It gives officials more time to conduct background checks by extending the background check review period from 3 to 10 days. It thereby closes the loophole that allowed the Charleston killer to purchase a gun after an incomplete background check. But the Senate refuses to the bring the bill to the floor for a vote at a time when mass murders are happening every day across our nation. It’s way past time for the Senate to heed the will of the people—who overwhelmingly support universal, complete background checks—and enact common sense gun measures that will save precious lives.

name: Gus M. Bilirakis
content:
Religious freedom is the most basic fundamental human right, and it must be protected. As the Chair of the International Religious Freedom Caucus and as a member of the Executive Committee of the Tom Lantos Human Rights Commission, I have fought throughout my congressional career to protect fundamental rights for people who are persecuted and discriminated against by oppressive governments. China has engaged in persecution against religious minorities for decades, and these unacceptable violations have only intensified and worsened with time. The father of one of my constituents, Zhou Deyong, is currently being detained for practicing his Falun Gong faith. I have reached out to Xi Jinping to express my concerns about this violation of basic human rights and called for his release. Click below to learn more.

THEEPOCHTIMES.COM
US Lawmaker Calls on Chinese Regime to Free Detained Relative of Falun Gong Adherents

name: Adriano Espaillat
content:
NY-13, your talent is unmatched.

We had a record number of submissions for this year's Congressional Art Competition — 50+ young artists submitted absolutely incredible pieces.

And here are this year's winners!

🥇 Mireille Vieux-Gresham, from LaGuardia High School, has won 1st place! Mireille submitted the first stunning portrait of Presidential Inauguration poet @Amanda Gorman, and it will hang in the U.S Capitol.

🥈 Emilia Pelegano-Titmuss, a student at the Bronx High School of Science, was selected for 2nd place! Emilia submitted the second incredible portrait of United States Capitol Police officer Eugene Goodman, and it will hang in my district office.

🥉 Finally, we had Columbia Secondary School students Naomi De Lashmutt and Shadi Yadollahi Khales tied for 3rd place. Naomi and Shadi submitted the final two stunning works that will also be hung in my district office.

Congratulations to this year's winners, and thanks to all the talented students in NY-13 who submitted artwork!

Be sure to take a look at all of this year's submissions here: ⤵️

https://youtu.be/HOfJp1rqxpU

name: Frank D. Lucas
content:
Following the tragic events of 9/11, Congress passed the 2002 authorization for use of military force, targeting terrorists regimes throughout Iraq and the surrounding region.

The 2002 AUMF was used to target and eliminate some of America's most well-known enemies- Saddam Hussein, Osama bin Laden, and Qasem Soleimani.

I have long supported re-examining the AUMF measures, but simply repealing the 2002 AUMF without replacing it with reformed war powers would only embolden terrorist adversaries in the region. While our mission has evolved in the region, we mustn't repeal AUMF measures without proper reforms.

FULL STATEMENT:

LUCAS.HOUSE.GOV
Lucas Statement on Repealing 2002 AUMF

name: Adam Smith
content:
Today the House confirmed, in a bipartisan way, that the repeal of an authorization for use of military force that is no longer applicable does not impede our national security. Circumstances on the ground in Iraq have changed dramatically since the passage of the 2002 AUMF.

Significantly, we now count the democratic Iraqi government our partner in our counterterrorism mission – as such, it is time to repeal this authority.

While today’s vote moves us one step closer to a full repeal of this outdated AUMF, there is more work to be done. I have said before that repeal of the 2002 AUMF is not enough.

I continue to be encouraged by the Biden-Harris Administration’s willingness to address outdated authorities. I look forward to working with the Administration and with my colleagues in Congress in reviewing existing authorities including the 2001 AUMF.

ADAMSMITH.HOUSE.GOV
Rep. Smith Statement on Bipartisan Vote to Repeal the 2002 AUMF

name: Sanford D. Bishop, Jr.
content:
The United States remains constantly vigilant, maintains the strongest military, and has alliances around the world to identify and counter the ever-evolving threats of terrorism. However, it is long past time to end the 2002 AUMF in Iraq. The solemn responsibility to declare war lies with Congress, and an authorization for the use of military force is never meant to be open-ended, lest we lose focus or indulge in mission creep. Out of respect to those who have given their lives in the defense of our country as well as families across America who bear the personal and economic burden of war, we need to ensure that their sacrifices are not treated as a blank check to perpetuate endless conflict.

BISHOP.HOUSE.GOV
CONGRESSMAN BISHOP VOTES TO REPEAL OUTDATED 2002 WAR AUTHORIZATION

name: Marc A. Veasey
content:
Today, I supported the repeal of the outdated Authorization of Military Force (AUMF) Against Iraq Resolution of 2002 to affirm that only Congress has the Constitutional power to declare war. The AUMF has long been used by the executive branch to sidestep Congressional War Powers and avoid accountability indefinitely. I hope the Senate will follow our lead and take up this bill in the upcoming days.

This year’s NATO Summit represented more than just 30 democratic allies coming together to discuss shared interests, threats, and challenges. Today’s Summit – following the G7 – was an opportunity for President Biden to demonstrate to our transatlantic allies and to the world that the United States is back and ready to lead.
